     <div class="main section" id="main">
      <div class="widget Blog" id="Blog1">
       <div class="blog-posts hfeed">
        <!-- google_ad_section_start(name=default) -->
        <div class="date-outer">
         <div class="date-posts">
          <div class="post-outer">
           <div class="post hentry uncustomized-post-template">
            <a name="5669926567051601065">
            </a>
            <div class="title">
             <h2>
              <a href="http://paleoking.blogspot.com/2014/09/dreadnoughtus-truth-and-myth.html">
               Dreadnoughtus - the Truth and the Myth
              </a>
             </h2>
             <div class="title-meta">
              <span class="author">
               Posted by Nima
              </span>
              <span class="clock">
               On Saturday, September 13, 2014
              </span>
              <span class="com">
               <a class="comment-link" href="http://paleoking.blogspot.com/2014/09/dreadnoughtus-truth-and-myth.html#comment-form" onclick="">
                4
comments
               </a>
              </span>
             </div>
            </div>
            <div class="post-header">
             <div class="post-header-line-1">
             </div>
            </div>
            <div class="postcover">
             <p>
              I knew this day was coming!
              <br/>
              <br/>
              Lacovara's titanosaur has been described, named, and even 3D imaged!
              <i>
               Dreadnoughtus schrani
              </i>
              , read about it here:
              <a href="http://www.nature.com/srep/2014/140904/srep06196/full/srep06196.html">
               http://www.nature.com/srep/2014/140904/srep06196/full/srep06196.html
              </a>
              .
              <br/>
              <br/>
              I saw this animal in preparation at the lab in Carnegie Museum long before it had a name, and I had the opportunity to speak with
              <a href="http://www.livescience.com/47662-astoundingly-huge-dinosaur-discovered-dreadnoughtus-video.html">
               Dr. Lacovara himself
              </a>
              at SVP 2010 and 2011 about this animal's morphology and likely lineage, so seeing the fruits of the Drexel team's work is personally satisfying. And unlike many instances of new dinosaur names, this one fits the bill perfectly.
              <i>
               Dreadnoughtus
              </i>
              is indeed a dreadnought of the dinosaurs. Not the only one by any means, but it's about time sauropods got some really imposing-sounding names, not just predatory theropods like T. rex. At some point sauropods really do get too big for any predator to mess with.
              <br/>
              <br/>
             </p>
             <div class="separator" style="clear: both; text-align: center;">
              <a href="http://1.bp.blogspot.com/-Mo6cumsJ7tY/VBTKxlk_qYI/AAAAAAAABWA/SghmYP_o86M/s1600/lacovara-standing-femur.jpg" imageanchor="1" style="margin-left: 1em; margin-right: 1em;">
               <img border="0" height="320" src="http://1.bp.blogspot.com/-Mo6cumsJ7tY/VBTKxlk_qYI/AAAAAAAABWA/SghmYP_o86M/s1600/lacovara-standing-femur.jpg" width="213"/>
              </a>
             </div>
             <br/>
             <br/>
             Now as usual with these giant dinosaur discoveries there are a number of myths floating around with the facts. Some of the most common rumors media reports that we can scrutinize are as follows:
             <br/>
             <br/>
             <u>
              1. This is the biggest dinosaur yet found.
             </u>
             <br/>
             Actually, no it's not.
             <i>
              Argentinosaurus, Alamosaurus, Puertasaurus, Ruyangosaurus,
             </i>
             the Chubut Monster,
             <i>
              "Huanghetitan" ruyangensis
             </i>
             , and maybe even
             <i>
              Paralititan
             </i>
             and
             <i>
              Argyrosaurus
             </i>
             sp. likely outclass it for raw size and mass. And there are a few brachiosaurs which also might be larger, including a very big referred specimen of
             <i>
              Brachiosaurus
             </i>
             itself. Of course neither specimen of Dreadnoughtus is fully grown (unfused scapula-coracoid suture is a dead giveaway of immaturity) so perhaps an adult
             <i>
              Dreadnoughtus
             </i>
             could rank higher in the "top 10 biggest". It is however among the biggest dinosaurs that are actually
             <i>
              complete enough
             </i>
             to reasonably estimate their size without much room for guesswork. But nobody is officially claiming it to be the "biggest" - we know based on general large titanosauriform proportions that most or all of the aforementioned animals are larger, even if estimating just how much larger is a bit more tricky.
             <br/>
             <br/>
             <div class="separator" style="clear: both; text-align: center;">
             </div>
             <div class="separator" style="clear: both; text-align: center;">
              <a href="http://2.bp.blogspot.com/-geBRfemnrIg/VBU8SAekXfI/AAAAAAAABXc/JPCZjDtwdaI/s1600/titanosaurs%2Bdreadnoughtus.jpg" imageanchor="1" style="margin-left: 1em; margin-right: 1em;">
               <img border="0" height="640" src="http://2.bp.blogspot.com/-geBRfemnrIg/VBU8SAekXfI/AAAAAAAABXc/JPCZjDtwdaI/s1600/titanosaurs%2Bdreadnoughtus.jpg" width="542"/>
              </a>
             </div>
             <br/>
             <br/>
             <u>
              2. This is the most complete giant titanosaur found.
             </u>
             <br/>
             This is technically true. Although it's missing most of the neck and ribs, which are largely present in
             <i>
              Futalognkosaurus
             </i>
             , the other contender for "most complete giant titanosaur". The fully tally of bones from the two
             <i>
              Dreadnoughtus
             </i>
             specimens adds up to more, especially considering the limb material, but the published diagrams and 3D scans still
             <i>
              look
             </i>
             less complete than
             <i>
              Futalognkosaurus
             </i>
             - when you composite all 3 specimens of Futa together, anyway. Surface area-wise, Futa's huge and deep neck bones at least make it appear more complete. And the referred juveniles contribute some limb material. Both animals appear to be similar in size.
             <br/>
             <br/>
             <div class="separator" style="clear: both; text-align: center;">
              <a href="http://4.bp.blogspot.com/-ebkMheGcLlQ/VBTSWLhj09I/AAAAAAAABWQ/hSxn1k_szVw/s1600/model.jpg" imageanchor="1" style="margin-left: 1em; margin-right: 1em;">
               <img border="0" height="180" src="http://4.bp.blogspot.com/-ebkMheGcLlQ/VBTSWLhj09I/AAAAAAAABWQ/hSxn1k_szVw/s1600/model.jpg" width="320"/>
              </a>
             </div>
             <br/>
             <br/>
             <div class="separator" style="clear: both; text-align: center;">
              <a href="http://1.bp.blogspot.com/-FoDR16q1R8A/VBTS2mHvhjI/AAAAAAAABWo/0ayHl1aSrlo/s1600/lab.jpg" imageanchor="1" style="margin-left: 1em; margin-right: 1em;">
               <img border="0" height="110" src="http://1.bp.blogspot.com/-FoDR16q1R8A/VBTS2mHvhjI/AAAAAAAABWo/0ayHl1aSrlo/s1600/lab.jpg" width="320"/>
              </a>
             </div>
             <div class="separator" style="clear: both; text-align: center;">
              <a href="http://3.bp.blogspot.com/-qq_7vKBSPSU/VBTS9XHoRCI/AAAAAAAABWw/UTE6_AKNeog/s1600/dreadnoughtus%2Bverts2.jpg" imageanchor="1" style="margin-left: 1em; margin-right: 1em;">
               <img border="0" height="191" src="http://3.bp.blogspot.com/-qq_7vKBSPSU/VBTS9XHoRCI/AAAAAAAABWw/UTE6_AKNeog/s1600/dreadnoughtus%2Bverts2.jpg" width="320"/>
              </a>
              <a href="http://2.bp.blogspot.com/-tVEXZPN0SP0/VBTTBidzKzI/AAAAAAAABW4/xNFL2ltuReU/s1600/dreadnoughtus%2Bverts1.jpg" imageanchor="1" style="margin-left: 1em; margin-right: 1em;">
               <img border="0" height="184" src="http://2.bp.blogspot.com/-tVEXZPN0SP0/VBTTBidzKzI/AAAAAAAABW4/xNFL2ltuReU/s1600/dreadnoughtus%2Bverts1.jpg" width="320"/>
              </a>
             </div>
             <br/>
             <u>
              3. This animal is a lognkosaur, as the paper seems to imply.
             </u>
             <br/>
             What's funny is that when the fossils were still under preparation back in 2010-11, both Dr. Lacovara and myself thought it might be something much more derived, like a record-sized
             <i>
              Aeolosaurus
             </i>
             -grade saltasaurid, due to the forward-slanted, antenna-like prezygapophyses in the tail. Of course to be fair, most of the fossils were in fragments at the time and had to be painstakingly glued back together, and when part or all of a caudal neural spine is broken off, many unrelated titanosaurs can look deceptively like "aeolosaurs". However, after analyzing the paper I can say that a lognkosaur-like position is indeed more plausible. This animal however isn't quite a lognkosaur. Close, but not quite.
             <br/>
             <br/>
             The upper humerus bulges upward medially, much more like
             <i>
              Argyrosaurus
             </i>
             and
             <i>
              Quetecsaurus
             </i>
             , which has a very
             <i>
              Argyrosaurus
             </i>
             -like hand shape. Unfortunately hand material is missing for
             <i>
              Dreadnoughtus
             </i>
             , but the arm bones look Argyrosaur-like enough. The femur is very wide and robust with a large, midlevel 4th trochanter, convex-curved upper margin, and a reduced lateral bulge - very different from any known lognkosaur femur, but very similar to the two huge "Argyrosaurus sp." femurs in the Field Museum. The dorsal vertebrae are pretty wide with substantial laminae making the neural spines triangular, but just not
             <i>
              as
             </i>
             wide as in true lognkosaurians. They do however bear a passing resemblance to the dorsals of "
             <i>
              Argyrosaurus
             </i>
             sp." (=
             <i>
              Elaltitan lilloi
             </i>
             ) specimen PVL 4628. The paper clusters it with
             <i>
              Malawisaurus
             </i>
             , which it places in a more derived position than true lognkosaurs - a position that isn't supported by the humerus and femur morphology and think should be re-examined. The Paleo King ranks this species as an Argyrosaurid, probably closest to
             <i>
              Quetecsaurus
             </i>
             . Which is a very good thing indeed, as it (along with the even odder
             <i>
              Quetecsaurus
             </i>
             ) greatly improves our knowledge of this obscure titanosaur family.
             <br/>
             <br/>
             <table align="center" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" class="tr-caption-container" style="margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; text-align: center;">
              <tbody>
               <tr>
                <td style="text-align: center;">
                 <a href="http://4.bp.blogspot.com/-K65y4OrTnp4/VBU-0ObMMnI/AAAAAAAABYA/Yu3VzIuWG-U/s1600/humerus%2Bcomparison.jpg" imageanchor="1" style="margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;">
                  <img border="0" height="309" src="http://4.bp.blogspot.com/-K65y4OrTnp4/VBU-0ObMMnI/AAAAAAAABYA/Yu3VzIuWG-U/s1600/humerus%2Bcomparison.jpg" width="320"/>
                 </a>
                </td>
               </tr>
               <tr>
                <td class="tr-caption" style="text-align: center;">
                 Bones NOT to scale here!
                </td>
               </tr>
              </tbody>
             </table>
             <br/>
             <div class="separator" style="clear: both; text-align: center;">
             </div>
             <div class="separator" style="clear: both; text-align: center;">
             </div>
             <table align="center" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" class="tr-caption-container" style="margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; text-align: center;">
              <tbody>
               <tr>
                <td style="text-align: center;">
                 <a href="http://2.bp.blogspot.com/-u_KWYBz668c/VBU86mhedOI/AAAAAAAABXk/IfZMbypXSZU/s1600/Dreadnoughtus%2Bfemur%2Bcomparison.jpg" imageanchor="1" style="margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;">
                  <img border="0" height="249" src="http://2.bp.blogspot.com/-u_KWYBz668c/VBU86mhedOI/AAAAAAAABXk/IfZMbypXSZU/s1600/Dreadnoughtus%2Bfemur%2Bcomparison.jpg" width="320"/>
                 </a>
                </td>
               </tr>
               <tr>
                <td class="tr-caption" style="text-align: center;">
                 Or here, though looks may deceive!
                </td>
               </tr>
              </tbody>
             </table>
             <br/>
             <u>
              4. The neck was horizontal (?!?!?!?)
             </u>
             <br/>
             The reality is that only two of the neck bones were found, and both exhibit pretty serious crushing. And the first 3 dorsal vertebrae are missing entirely, with the 4th being seriously crushed as well. So it's very difficult if not impossible to reconstruct its neck posture accurately. The honest answer is that
             <u>
              we don't know
             </u>
             what
             <i>
              Dreadnoughtus
             </i>
             ' neck posture was. But I think it's a pretty good guess that the neck was vertical or semi-vertical as in
             <i>
              Futalognkosaurus
             </i>
             , not horizontal as in the published skeletal in the paper. We are definitely dealing with a high-browser here. Titanosaurs of such large size usually have the extremely long and vertical necks of high browsers - there is no point in wasting such necks to only bend down and eat ferns like
             <i>
              Saltasaurus
             </i>
             or
             <i>
              Diplodocus
             </i>
             . Even the paltry tooth material found with
             <i>
              Dreadnoughtus
             </i>
             is that of a high-browsing conifer eater. The 9th(?) cervical is big enough to indicate an even longer neck than
             <i>
              Futalognkosaurus
             </i>
             , and even with the 3D model omitting any speculative reconstruction of the hands (and leaving precious little space for them), the shoulders of
             <i>
              Dreadnoughtus
             </i>
             are still higher than its hips. Add in hands of correct lognkosaur or argyrosaur proportions, and this will tilt up the torso and shoulders even further. And the general rule with all high-shouldered sauropods is that they also tend to be high-browsers, regardless of neck length. So we have two patterns of evidence in favor of a vertical neck.
             <br/>
             <br/>
             <table align="center" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" class="tr-caption-container" style="margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; text-align: center;">
              <tbody>
               <tr>
                <td style="text-align: center;">
                 <a href="http://4.bp.blogspot.com/-_qy1l7U9ogY/VBTSoaxNrFI/AAAAAAAABWg/kH3qPO8NCsQ/s1600/Dreadnoughtus%2B3D%2Bmodel1.jpg" imageanchor="1" style="margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;">
                  <img border="0" height="139" src="http://4.bp.blogspot.com/-_qy1l7U9ogY/VBTSoaxNrFI/AAAAAAAABWg/kH3qPO8NCsQ/s1600/Dreadnoughtus%2B3D%2Bmodel1.jpg" width="320"/>
                 </a>
                </td>
               </tr>
               <tr>
                <td class="tr-caption" style="text-align: center;">
                 3d model scan of the actual fossils. Even with the arm not raised high enough to leave space for the hands, the shoulders rise above the hips. Every well-preserved macronarian with this pattern exhibits a more or less vertical neck. Note that the back is pretty straight here.
                </td>
               </tr>
              </tbody>
             </table>
             <table align="center" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" class="tr-caption-container" style="margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; text-align: center;">
              <tbody>
               <tr>
                <td style="text-align: center;">
                 <a href="http://4.bp.blogspot.com/-gMNho3ZMeew/VBU8_dkh_zI/AAAAAAAABXs/J9AbeS4V-f4/s1600/Dreadnoughtus%2Blimbs.jpg" imageanchor="1" style="margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;">
                  <img border="0" height="312" src="http://4.bp.blogspot.com/-gMNho3ZMeew/VBU8_dkh_zI/AAAAAAAABXs/J9AbeS4V-f4/s1600/Dreadnoughtus%2Blimbs.jpg" width="320"/>
                 </a>
                </td>
               </tr>
               <tr>
                <td class="tr-caption" style="text-align: center;">
                 Original skeletal from paper - the neck seems to be horizontal to make room for more figures? The back is oddly curved, which isn't evidence by anything in the fossils, and the dorsal spines just look wrong. Where's the backsweep?
                </td>
               </tr>
              </tbody>
             </table>
             <table align="center" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" class="tr-caption-container" style="margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; text-align: center;">
              <tbody>
               <tr>
                <td style="text-align: center;">
                 <a href="http://1.bp.blogspot.com/-s_4LEHfJnbM/VBU9lqJn9fI/AAAAAAAABX0/JaAL46kn6JA/s1600/Dreadnoughtus%2Bskeletal%2Bcorrected.jpg" imageanchor="1" style="margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;">
                  <img border="0" height="207" src="http://1.bp.blogspot.com/-s_4LEHfJnbM/VBU9lqJn9fI/AAAAAAAABX0/JaAL46kn6JA/s1600/Dreadnoughtus%2Bskeletal%2Bcorrected.jpg" width="320"/>
                 </a>
                </td>
               </tr>
               <tr>
                <td class="tr-caption" style="text-align: center;">
                 Very hastily corrected version with correct-sized hands and a straighter back and more vertical neck. Now that's better!
                </td>
               </tr>
              </tbody>
             </table>
             Unfortunately these days (thanks in no small part to a certain wispy white mustache from outside the field) the convention in many dinosaur papers seems to be to illustrate sauropod necks horizontal since it's seen as more "conservative" and "safe" even if it isn't meant to be literally accurate or isn't the main focus of the paper. Never mind that it wastes neck length, puts much more strain on the span of the neck than a vertical posture, and that most macronarian necks weren't built for tolerating horizontal strain for any substantial length of time... of course it's possible Lacovara and co. may have just wanted to save vertical space per page in an already large paper (publishing is getting expensive as many of us know) so I can't judge their reasoning on this particular case.
             <br/>
             <br/>
             <br/>
             <u>
              5.
              <i>
               Dreadnoughtus
              </i>
              and
              <i>
               Puertasaurus
              </i>
              were basically best chums.
             </u>
             <br/>
             Doubtful. Although they were found very close together (something like only 13 miles apart) in Santa Cruz province in the far south of Argentina, their time horizons may be different. The exact stratigraphy of the
             <i>
              Dreadnoughtus
             </i>
             site is still a bit murky, and even if it is Maastrichtian in age, it may still be separated from
             <i>
              Puertasaurus
             </i>
             by hundreds of thousands of years if not more. And even if they did live at the same time, they may not have been buddies. Big sauropods in similar feeding niches were just as likely to compete over resources as share them. Notice that term
             <i>
              similar
             </i>
             niches. This did not mean that big herbivores always butted heads (or tails, as the case may be). Sauropods in vastly different feeding niches (such as brachiosaurs and diplodocids in the Morrison and Tendaguru formations) tended to coexist just fine.
             <br/>
             <br/>
             Plus, if the subadult type specimen of
             <i>
              Dreadnoughtus
             </i>
             (or one of similar size, around 50-60 tons) crossed paths with the
             <i>
              Puertasaurus
             </i>
             type (around 90-110 tons, which may or may not be an adult) then maybe "dread-nought" may have stopped being such an appropriate label! Comparing the dorsals of
             <i>
              Dreadnoughtus
             </i>
             with the one found from
             <i>
              Puertasaurus
             </i>
             , you will soon see that while
             <i>
              Dreadnoughtus
             </i>
             may be huge, it's definitely not in the same league.
             <br/>
             <br/>
             <br/>
             <br/>
             <div style="clear: both;">
             </div>
            </div>

            <a name="7685028331749233735">

            <div class="title">
             <h2>
              <a href="http://paleoking.blogspot.com/2014/07/is-french-monster-euhelopodid.html">
               Is the French Monster a Euhelopodid?
              </a>
             </h2>
             <div class="title-meta">
              <span class="author">
               Posted by Nima
              </span>
              <span class="clock">
               On Thursday, July 10, 2014
              </span>
              <span class="com">
               <a class="comment-link" href="http://paleoking.blogspot.com/2014/07/is-french-monster-euhelopodid.html#comment-form" onclick="">
                0
comments
               </a>
              </span>
             </div>
            </div>
            <div class="post-header">
             <div class="post-header-line-1">
             </div>
            </div>
            <div class="postcover">
             <p>
              One of these days we may see a paper come out about this. France, as you may know, contains
              <a href="http://1.bp.blogspot.com/_u6CUqDWU5nw/TUY3cEyjn8I/AAAAAAAAAwo/DlMMULFFhG4/s1600/colossal+titanosaur+femur+from+France%2521.jpg">
               a dinosaur of truly gigantic proportions
              </a>
              (and no, I'm not talking about the Algerian species
              <i>
               "Brachiosaurus" nougaredi
              </i>
              which seems to have disappeared into a black hole somewhere in Paris). No, this one's a local. A new "titanosaur" known only as the French Monster, or the giant of Angeac, has turned up in the past few years in a bone bed which contains a huge jumble of Early Cretaceous dinosaurs of various sizes - everything from baby abelisaurs to massive hundred-foot sauropods.
              <br/>
              <br/>
              Except it's not really a titanosaur, is it?
              <br/>
              <br/>
              The French Monster is another one of those legendary or semi-legendary sauropods which
              <i>
               should
              </i>
              have a name and a formal description, though it's unlikely most of them ever will. Even the pictures evoke something rarely seen in the fossil record.
              <br/>
              <br/>
             </p>
             <div class="separator" style="clear: both; text-align: center;">
             </div>
             <br/>
             <div class="separator" style="clear: both; text-align: center;">
              <a href="http://1.bp.blogspot.com/-hlyuuqVe2HU/U736Kmas7rI/AAAAAAAABTE/SVwKH0pMmdg/s1600/Angeac+-+colossal+titanosaur+femur+from+France!.jpg" imageanchor="1" style="margin-left: 1em; margin-right: 1em;">
               <img border="0" height="320" src="http://1.bp.blogspot.com/-hlyuuqVe2HU/U736Kmas7rI/AAAAAAAABTE/SVwKH0pMmdg/s1600/Angeac+-+colossal+titanosaur+femur+from+France!.jpg" width="240"/>
              </a>
              <a href="http://1.bp.blogspot.com/-6CtXdn-QKVM/U7369xbm5bI/AAAAAAAABTc/itRHQq30YQw/s1600/Angeac+giant+femur+4.jpg" imageanchor="1" style="margin-left: 1em; margin-right: 1em;">
               <img border="0" height="320" src="http://1.bp.blogspot.com/-6CtXdn-QKVM/U7369xbm5bI/AAAAAAAABTc/itRHQq30YQw/s1600/Angeac+giant+femur+4.jpg" width="213"/>
              </a>
             </div>
             <div class="separator" style="clear: both; text-align: center;">
              <a href="http://2.bp.blogspot.com/-QGZI4IeUVR4/U736qrHpCXI/AAAAAAAABTM/1WDv3Fi_yVw/s1600/Angeac+giant+femur+5.jpg" imageanchor="1" style="margin-left: 1em; margin-right: 1em;">
               <img border="0" height="320" src="http://2.bp.blogspot.com/-QGZI4IeUVR4/U736qrHpCXI/AAAAAAAABTM/1WDv3Fi_yVw/s1600/Angeac+giant+femur+5.jpg" width="213"/>
              </a>
              <a href="http://1.bp.blogspot.com/-uv8il-tmjqI/U736z8waaBI/AAAAAAAABTU/ho-pu6hd6n0/s1600/angeac+giant+femur.jpg" imageanchor="1" style="margin-left: 1em; margin-right: 1em;">
               <img border="0" height="320" src="http://1.bp.blogspot.com/-uv8il-tmjqI/U736z8waaBI/AAAAAAAABTU/ho-pu6hd6n0/s1600/angeac+giant+femur.jpg" width="213"/>
              </a>
             </div>
             <br/>
             Mainly the image that sticks in your mind is the very long and oddly blackened right femur, over 2.2m long, with which everyone seems to be "doing the
             <a href="data:image/jpeg;base64,">
              Jensen
             </a>
             " though none of them come close to getting it right.
             <br/>
             <br/>
             But there is much more to the Angeac-Charente site where this bone was found. There appears to be part of a second femur also recovered at the site, and possible rib fragments. And different individuals of this species have been found, with the fossils in different shades of mineralization.
             <br/>
             <br/>
             <div class="separator" style="clear: both; text-align: center;">
              <a href="http://2.bp.blogspot.com/-jfiCnovB_fw/U739QDQPh8I/AAAAAAAABTo/8h7TTaZjmSY/s1600/Angeac+giant+sauropod+femur.jpg" imageanchor="1" style="margin-left: 1em; margin-right: 1em;">
               <img border="0" height="205" src="http://2.bp.blogspot.com/-jfiCnovB_fw/U739QDQPh8I/AAAAAAAABTo/8h7TTaZjmSY/s1600/Angeac+giant+sauropod+femur.jpg" width="320"/>
              </a>
             </div>
             <br/>
             <div class="separator" style="clear: both; text-align: center;">
              <a href="http://3.bp.blogspot.com/-3712TZUp1vs/U739jICrI9I/AAAAAAAABTw/8tuk-Ev1gTI/s1600/angeac+bones.jpg" imageanchor="1" style="margin-left: 1em; margin-right: 1em;">
               <img border="0" height="213" src="http://3.bp.blogspot.com/-3712TZUp1vs/U739jICrI9I/AAAAAAAABTw/8tuk-Ev1gTI/s1600/angeac+bones.jpg" width="320"/>
              </a>
             </div>
             GIGANTIC tail vertebrae and toe bones. Over a foot in length or diameter. Note the cheesy scaled-up mid-90s "Brachiosaurus" skeleton model designed by Dale Russell and Ely Kish - these things originally came in a screw-cap plastic egg, and were the highlight of every kid's otherwise dull-as-doorknobs trip to T.J. Maxx. Some of you may be too young to remember... The model isn't 6 feet tall like it may appear, it's on the shelf, not the floor!
             <br/>
             <br/>
             <div class="separator" style="clear: both; text-align: center;">
              <a href="http://1.bp.blogspot.com/-IW8oBlRThHk/U74AV7NotFI/AAAAAAAABT8/JstFTbubuTE/s1600/sauropod+verts+and+toe+bones,+possible+tibia+end+-+Angeac.jpg" imageanchor="1" style="margin-left: 1em; margin-right: 1em;">
               <img border="0" height="247" src="http://1.bp.blogspot.com/-IW8oBlRThHk/U74AV7NotFI/AAAAAAAABT8/JstFTbubuTE/s1600/sauropod+verts+and+toe+bones,+possible+tibia+end+-+Angeac.jpg" width="320"/>
              </a>
             </div>
             The heavy toe bones and caudals. These may be from multiple individuals.
             <br/>
             <br/>
             <div class="separator" style="clear: both; text-align: center;">
              <a href="http://1.bp.blogspot.com/-rvdooeP7cjg/U74BIg6WUGI/AAAAAAAABUE/pUf-MBrU0Pg/s1600/sauropod+teeth,+Angeac-Charente.jpg" imageanchor="1" style="margin-left: 1em; margin-right: 1em;">
               <img border="0" height="102" src="http://1.bp.blogspot.com/-rvdooeP7cjg/U74BIg6WUGI/AAAAAAAABUE/pUf-MBrU0Pg/s1600/sauropod+teeth,+Angeac-Charente.jpg" width="320"/>
              </a>
             </div>
             <div class="separator" style="clear: both; text-align: center;">
              <a href="http://2.bp.blogspot.com/-_ZN6oL-hYbI/U74BO79hzKI/AAAAAAAABUM/X9gkwltATlU/s1600/sauropod+tooth,+Angeac-Charente.jpg" imageanchor="1" style="margin-left: 1em; margin-right: 1em;">
               <img border="0" height="207" src="http://2.bp.blogspot.com/-_ZN6oL-hYbI/U74BO79hzKI/AAAAAAAABUM/X9gkwltATlU/s1600/sauropod+tooth,+Angeac-Charente.jpg" width="320"/>
              </a>
             </div>
             Some teeth were found, very well preserved and encrusted with mineral deposits formed in fossilization.
             <br/>
             <br/>
             These teeth have a very basal appearance, and so the labeling of this animal as a titanosaur is unlikely. The teeth could easily pass for Brachiosaur teeth. But there is more than just this first indication what what we are seeing may not be a true titanosaur.
             <br/>
             <br/>
             <div class="separator" style="clear: both; text-align: center;">
              <a href="http://3.bp.blogspot.com/-uVKRa1uHcuE/U74CV8LA5hI/AAAAAAAABUU/ZmatWSmTMP8/s1600/giant+humerus+perhaps...+angeac.jpg" imageanchor="1" style="margin-left: 1em; margin-right: 1em;">
               <img border="0" height="205" src="http://3.bp.blogspot.com/-uVKRa1uHcuE/U74CV8LA5hI/AAAAAAAABUU/ZmatWSmTMP8/s1600/giant+humerus+perhaps...+angeac.jpg" width="320"/>
              </a>
             </div>
             The femur and the other pieces were apparently packed and shipped to a museum. It's not clear if this is in Paris or elsewhere. The femur is crushed and snapped in a few places but its total length is still preserved. A cast and wall mount were rapidly made. And this is the peculiar part.
             <br/>
             <br/>
             <div class="separator" style="clear: both; text-align: center;">
              <a href="http://4.bp.blogspot.com/-fDglP8WStTE/U74EJq595BI/AAAAAAAABUg/ii2HyhWDFVc/s1600/French+monster+-+CAST+of+femur,+face-on.jpg" imageanchor="1" style="margin-left: 1em; margin-right: 1em;">
               <img border="0" height="320" src="http://4.bp.blogspot.com/-fDglP8WStTE/U74EJq595BI/AAAAAAAABUg/ii2HyhWDFVc/s1600/French+monster+-+CAST+of+femur,+face-on.jpg" width="213"/>
              </a>
             </div>
             Here you see the femur, fragments of another, and a rib. Apparently this is a part of the full wall mount you see in the background of the previous picture. It's evident both that there was crushing and that very little erosion has happened. The most unusual things about this femur are the very long femoral head, and the odd lower end, with its inner condyle extending lower than the outer one. This is the exact opposite of when you see in derived titanosaurs. But is is a classic femur morph in a group which is close to basal titanosaurs.
             <br/>
             <br/>
             Between brachiosaurs and basal somphospondyli (creatures like
             <i>
              Chubutisaurus
             </i>
             ,
             <i>
              Ligabuesaurus
             </i>
             , and some would say,
             <i>
              Paluxysaurus
             </i>
             and
             <i>
              Sauroposeidon
             </i>
             ) and true titanosaurs, there was an amazing radiation of transitional forms. These appear to form at least two major families: Euhelopodidae, and Acrofornica (tall-arches). Both are characterized by extremely long necks, high cervical counts, and bifid neural spines in the neck. The Acrofornica are further distinguished by very tall neural arches, high diapophyses, and nearly no neural spine in the dorsals. They tend to have well-separated sacral ribs, whereas those of euhelopodids tend to be extensively fused together. And whereas euhelopodids (or at least some of them) have procoelous tail vertebrae (anticipating derived titanosaurs!) the tails of acrofornicans revert back to simple amphiplatyan tails, as in basal titanosaurs.
             <br/>
             <br/>
             After about 3 years of morphometric comparisons between various elements and overlaps between different specimens (some of them very fragmentary) the following family tree slowly began to reveal itself. This is
             <b>
              not
             </b>
             a complete family tree of titanosauriformes; only some of the more well-known ones intermediate between brachiosaurs and titanosaurs are included here.
             <br/>
             <br/>
             <div class="separator" style="clear: both; text-align: center;">
              <a href="http://4.bp.blogspot.com/-_IzppY9kQ0E/U75LbjWxCtI/AAAAAAAABVQ/W86OEocsrz4/s1600/Titanosauriform+family+tree+-+somphospondyli.jpg" imageanchor="1" style="margin-left: 1em; margin-right: 1em;">
               <img border="0" height="371" src="http://4.bp.blogspot.com/-_IzppY9kQ0E/U75LbjWxCtI/AAAAAAAABVQ/W86OEocsrz4/s1600/Titanosauriform+family+tree+-+somphospondyli.jpg" width="400"/>
              </a>
             </div>
             <div class="separator" style="clear: both; text-align: center;">
             </div>
             And in the comparisons between different elements, specifically femora, the French Monster appears to belong in this transitional "gap" rather than in the more derived true Titanosauria. Previously I had put several hypotheses out there, what the French Monster may have been. Perhaps a lognkosaur, possibly a
             <i>
              Malawisaurus
             </i>
             -grade stem lognkosaur. Perhaps an oddly slender Antarctosaur of
             <i>
              Pellegrinisaurus
             </i>
             ilk. Maybe even a nemegtosaurid like
             <i>
              Huabeisa
             </i>
             -
             <b>
              wait
             </b>
             a minute, that one's not even considered a nemegtosaur anymore! That's the great thing about
             <a href="http://www.plosone.org/article/info%3Adoi%2F10.1371%2Fjournal.pone.0069375">
              finally using digital photos
             </a>
             ... they clear up all sorts of confusion - which Pang &amp; Cheng had forgotten to do in the original blurry description.
             <br/>
             <br/>
             Well it turns out that the French Monster is more like
             <i>
              Huabeisaurus
             </i>
             than previously realized. Both are closer to
             <i>
              Euhelopus
             </i>
             and the acrofornicans than to true titanosaurs.
             <br/>
             <br/>
             Complicating matters is the fact that some lognkosaurian titanosaurs have a protruding femoral head and a high and prominent lateral bulge, which differs from all other titanosaurs, and converges on that of some euhelopodids and acrofornicans. However the distal end of the femur follows radically different patterns in the two lineages. Here's the comparison of posterior views, you be the judge (not to scale):
             <br/>
             <br/>
             <div class="separator" style="clear: both; text-align: center;">
              <a href="http://4.bp.blogspot.com/-PRavXpPMw0k/U75FkBKfbhI/AAAAAAAABVA/mQWzjrhqATc/s1600/Is+it+a+euhelopodid2.jpg" imageanchor="1" style="margin-left: 1em; margin-right: 1em;">
               <img border="0" height="268" src="http://4.bp.blogspot.com/-PRavXpPMw0k/U75FkBKfbhI/AAAAAAAABVA/mQWzjrhqATc/s1600/Is+it+a+euhelopodid2.jpg" width="400"/>
              </a>
             </div>
             So far the morphology of the French Monster's femur (the long and slender femoral head, the tibial condyle being longer and more massive than the fibular condyle, the lateral bulge high on the femur) appear more like a basal somphospondyl than a titanosaur. Most specifically, it resembles
             <i>
              Paluxysaurus
             </i>
             , and to a lesser degree,
             <i>
              Huabeisaurus
             </i>
             . The distal end of the
             <i>
              Chubutisaurus
             </i>
             femur is too eroded to make a good comparison on the condyles. All the same, the basal lineage of this unusual animal look much clearer now. The French Monster points to a radiation of basal sonphospondyli well outside Asia in the early Cretaceous.
             <i>
              Angolatitan
             </i>
             was the first euhelopodid to be described outside Asia, proving that the clade was not an exclusively Chinese one - and there are rumors of some similar fossils in Europe as well. If it's a chubutisaur, it would be the first to be found outside the Americas.
             <br/>
             <br/>
             Perhaps the biggest oddity of all is how slender the French Monster's femur is. The crushing is mostly from front to back, not lateral. So it really was this narrow. There is a possibility then, that this animal was not even close to the maximum size possible. As an adult it may have been more robust. There is no coracoid or scapula material, so the degree of suture fusion in the shoulders (and thus the animal's maturity) is open to speculation.
             <br/>
             <br/>
             As far as I can see it, this dinosaur is most likely a chubutisaur (or whatever
             <i>
              Paluxysaurus
             </i>
             is, seeing as it's more or lesss totally busted as a purported brachiosaur), but may also belong in acrofornica or euhelopodidae depending on how the cladistics stack up. In any case it's huge and unusual, and maybe soon we may get to see a description and some idea of its overall proportions.
             <br/>
             <br/>
             <br/>
             <div style="clear: both;">
             </div>
            </div>
